Horizontal Decoupling: Layout-First UI Dev (Presentational & Page Components)

Last updated: March 3rd, 2024

Topics: Layout-first, component-first, MVC, dumb presentational components, page components

Major Topics: Architectural Components

Now that we’ve got the screens, we know what architectural components (frontend, backend, libraries, tools) we need, we’ll start by coding out the frontend. To do so, we’re going to apply Horizontal Decoupling to build out the View portion of MVC on the frontend.

Lesson goals

In this lesson, we’ll:

  • See the most common way to kick off your frontend work at the Code-First level
  • Discuss two types of frontend component patterns typically used to build layouts (dumb presentational & page/view components) and the role they play with respect to MVC
  • Get the layout for the frontend setup

Essential in Focus: Horizontal Decoupling — where to start our work from?

There are a number of ways we can start our work on the frontend.

But which one is most popular?

Let’s check the polls!

Overwhelmingly, it appears that most developers tend to start by building out the view — which involves building out the entirety of the layout first, and then continuing inwards to construct components from it afterwards.

Since that’s what’s common — especially at the Code-First level, that’s what we’ll do here.

Frontend component patterns

In building out these views, you’ll need to rely upon a few different patterns.

Here are the two key ones that I think have the greatest impact at this level.

Functional (dumb) presentational components

The first are functional dumb presentational components.

You’ve probably seen these or are already well familiar.

If you’re not, these are components that are completely free of internal state, side-effects — they take in data, present it, and that’s about it.

You can also link interactions like button clicks or keypresses to behaviour, but here is not the place you handle those things.

import React from 'react';

const ItemList = ({ items, onItemClick }) => (
  <ul>
    {items.map((item, index) => (
      <li key={index} onClick={() => onItemClick(index)}>
        {item}
      </li>
    ))}
  </ul>
);

export default ItemList;

(alternatively) Stateful dumb presentational components

This is another variation of presentational component. Not too much different, except that it’s stateful.

The simplest example I can show you is the following:

import React, { useState } from 'react';

const Counter = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const increment = () => {
    setCount(count + 1);
  };

  const decrement = () => {
    setCount(count - 1);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Counter</h1>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={increment}>Increment</button>
      <button onClick={decrement}>Decrement</button>
    </div>
  );
};

export default Counter;

The idea behind this?

Sometimes your component needs some state, but that state isn’t really relevant to anything else other than the component itself.

I kinda hate simple examples because they don’t really convey the essence well (there’s no soul, man).

If you’d like, you can also take a look at the RegistrationForm I’ve built out for your assignment.

It’s much more realistic.

Page (container) components

Secondly is the Page (or container) component.

While some developers don’t like to make any distinctions about the pages and presentational components, I prefer to designate a folder specifically for pages and to make them a core pattern in how I build views.

A page/container component is where you:

  • handle page or view state (non-global state)
  • link together other components
  • structure the view out, from the highest level,
  • and decide what happens with the interactions that your presentational components emit

Here’s an example building on what we just saw.

import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import ItemList from './ItemList';

const ItemListPage = () => {
  const [items, setItems] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    // Fetch data from an API
    fetch('<https://api.example.com/items>')
      .then(response => response.json())
      .then(data => setItems(data))
      .catch(error => console.error('Error fetching items:', error));
  }, []);

  const handleItemClick = index => {
    // Handle item click
    console.log('Item clicked:', items[index]);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Item List</h1>
      <ItemList items={items} onItemClick={handleItemClick} />
    </div>
  );
};

export default ItemListPage;

Separation of concerns: MVC on the Frontend

How do these frontend patterns match up w/ MVC?

Dumb presentational components are most definitely your View Layer components.

Page (Container) components tend to play more of the role of the Controller, even though we haven’t done any sort of coordinating or controlling just yet.

Huh? Coordinating and controlling? Ah, my Responsibility-First is showing. You’ll learn about this in the Responsibility-First Phase of Craftship, but there’s the concept of Object Stereotypes — stereotypical types of objects that we encounter in the wild. There’s about 6 of them, and the Controller is one of them. The controller’s job is to control and coordinate interactions between other objects. If you’re interested in going down that rabbit hole before we continue, you can take a look at this article.

Why bother?

Why bother with the differentiation?

Can’t a component just be a component?

Yeah, you could make no distinction, but in terms of Abstraction, there are too many benefits we get from when we DO make the distinction.

By Horizontally Decoupling concerns, we get all of the benefits of Abstraction.

Localizing changes to a single abstraction layer…

  • makes it easy to find the correct abstraction to change for a specific developer use case
  • makes it easier to maintain individual components
  • gives us better language and a conceptual model to understand the work we do, which makes it easier to communicate with others

Getting started w/ the MainPage View, Layout & Components

At this point, I’ve got my frontend & backend folders setup, dependencies installed, so now I can go ahead and set up the layouts and components using this *Layout to Component-*based approach.

I’ll focus solely on everything presentational from MainPage and down, allowing you to do the rest for your assignment.

1. Setting up the MainPage

If you’ve built frontends before, this should feel pretty much like breathing to you at this point.

First, I’ll set up the main page route.

frontend/src/App.tsx

import "./App.css";

import { BrowserRouter } from "react-router-dom";
import { Route, Routes } from "react-router-dom";
import { MainPage } from "./pages/mainPage";

function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <meta name="color-scheme" content="light only"></meta>
      <Routes>
        <Route path="/" element={<MainPage />} />
      </Routes>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}

export default App;

Then I’ll actually create the MainPage component.

frontend/src/pages/mainPage.tsx

import React, { useEffect, useState } from "react";

export const MainPage = () => {
  // We'll load posts and all of that here later.

  return (
    <Layout>
      
    </Layout>
  );
};

And then I’ll think about the layout and what needs to go within it.

2. Building the layout

I like to look at the screens and logically try to make sense of the layout.

What’s consistent? How do we organize things similarly on pages?

If I look at the view, this is what I tend to see.

I see a:

  • Layout area which contains two components
  • A Header
  • and a Content area

Nice and easy. I’ll create the layout component and put the Content and Header components within it.

components/layout.tsx

import React from 'react';
import { Content } from './content';

export const Content = ({ children }: any) => (
  <div className='content-container'>
    {children}
  </div>
)

export const Layout = ({ children }: any) => (
  <>
    <Header/>
    <Content>
      {children}
    </Content>
  </>
)

I’ll build the Header.

components/header.tsx

import React from "react";
import logo from "../assets/dddforumlogo.png";
import { Link } from "react-router-dom";

const Logo = () => (
  <div id="app-logo">
    <img src={logo}></img>
  </div>
);
const TitleAndSubmission = () => (
  <div id="title-container">
    <h1>Domain-Driven Designers</h1>
    <h3>Where awesome domain driven designers are made</h3>
    <Link to={"/submit"}>submit</Link>
  </div>
);

const HeaderActionButton = ({ user }: { user: any }) => (
  <div id="header-action-button">
    {user ? (
      <div>
        <div>{user.username}</div>
        <u>
          <div>logout</div>
        </u>
      </div>
    ) : (
      <Link to="/join">Join</Link>
    )}
  </div>
);

const shouldShowActionButton = (pathName: string) => {
  return pathName !== "/join";
};

export const Header = ({ pathName }: { pathName: string }) => {
  return (
    <header id="header" className="flex align-center">
      <Logo />
      <TitleAndSubmission />
      {shouldShowActionButton(location.pathname) ? (
        <HeaderActionButton user={{ username: '@john' }} />
      ) : (
        ""
      )}
    </header>
  );
};

And that should do it.

Design Principle: I could also move the header outside of the layout, but I’m operating from the design principle that to Move Components Upwards When Necessary. If we need to, we’ll discover that as we go.

3. Using dummy data to present posts

And because we haven’t actually connected this to a database or anything yet, let’s just use dummy data to fill in what we’d expect to see on the frontend.

I’m going to need a few more components on the main page, namely a PostsViewSwitcher and a PostsList which will take in a list of Posts.

frontend/src/pages/mainPage.tsx


import React, { useEffect, useState } from "react";
import { Layout } from "../components/layout";
import { PostsList } from "../components/postsList";
import { PostsViewSwitcher } from "../components/postsViewSwitcher";
import { api } from "../api";

export const MainPage = () => {
  const posts = [{ ... }];

  return (
    <Layout>
      <PostsViewSwitcher />
      <PostsList
        posts={posts}
      />
    </Layout>
  );
};

And lastly, I’ll show you how I’ve set up PostsList.


import React from 'react'

import { Link } from "react-router-dom";
import arrow from "../assets/arrow.svg";
import moment from 'moment';

type Vote = { id: number, postId: number, voteType: 'Upvote' | 'Downvote' };
type Comment = {};

type Post = {
  title: string;
  dateCreated: string;
  memberPostedBy: any;
  comments: Comment[];
  votes: Vote[]
};

function computeVoteCount(votes: Vote[]) {
  let count = 0;
  votes.forEach((v) => v.voteType === 'Upvote' ? count++ : count--);
  return count;
}

export const PostsList = ({ posts }: { posts: Post[] }) => (
  <div className="posts-list">
    {posts.map((post, key) => (
      <div className="post-item" key={key}>
        <div className="post-item-votes">
          <div className="post-item-upvote">
            <img src={arrow} />
          </div>
          <div>{computeVoteCount(post.votes)}</div>
          <div className="post-item-downvote">
            <img src={arrow} />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div className="post-item-content">
          <div className="post-item-title">{post.title}</div>
          <div className="post-item-details">
          <div>{moment(post.dateCreated).fromNow()}</div>
          <Link to={`/member/${post.memberPostedBy.user.username}`}>
            by {post.memberPostedBy.user.username}
          </Link>
          <div>
            {post.comments.length}{" "}
            {post.comments.length !== 1 ? `comments` : "comment"}
          </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>
);

Since you asked we identify improvements. Personally, I would lift the "map" up to the MainPage component.

Then rather create a "PostItem" component. There's a lot of function calls within JSX, which as a personal preference, I don't like. I would prefer to do this within the component logic section (above the return statement), and just refer to the vars in the JSX.

The PostsList component in this case would be unnecessary. And the array that we need to loop through is close to the API call site (even though it's hard coded in your example), which makes the UI feel less like "magic" to me.
